            <biogHist>
                <p>Archibald Sinclair was born to parents Archibald Sinclair, printer and publisher,
                    and Ann Sinclair n√©e McEwan, both natives of Islay. Sinclair's father was
                    founding President of the Glasgow Islay Association (at whose inaugural meeting
                    Archibald was present aged 12), and also founder of the Glasgow based Celtic
                    Press. After his father's death in 1870, Sinclair took on both roles in turn,
                    successfully growing his father's business and becoming a leading figure in the
                    preservation and dissemination of Gaelic language and literature. In addition to
                    printing and publishing Gaelic literature, including translations from English,
                    he personally collected, edited and published a well-received collection of
                    Gaelic poetry, <span style="bibTitle">An t-Oranaiche</span> [The Gaelic
                    Songster].</p>
                <p>Sinclair married Catherine Johnston in 1877, and by the 1891 census they were
                    living in Rutherglen with two sons and a daughter, including a third Archibald
                    Sinclair (11). He died only eight years later in Glasgow, the cause of death
                    recorded as 'Bronchitis, Pleurisy'.</p>
                <p>Sinclair appears in the passing in one of Alexander Carmichael's notebooks, with
                    a pencil addition to one story reading, 'Sent to Archd Sinclair 62 Argyle St
                    Glasgow in May 1877'.</p>
